Within the Stratos DC, the Nautilus storage server hosts a directory named /data, serving as a repository for various developers non-confidential data. Developer mariyam has requested a copy of their data stored in /data/mariyam. The System Admin team has provided the following steps to fulfill this request:

a. Create a compressed archive named mariyam.tar.gz of the /data/mariyam directory.

b. Transfer the archive to the /home directory on the Storage Server.

What is the task?

You are required to:

Create a compressed archive (mariyam.tar.gz) of the directory

/data/mariyam


Move (store) that archive in:

/home


This is performed on the Storage Server inside the Stratos Datacenter.

In simple terms:
ğŸ‘‰ Package Mariyamâ€™s data safely into a single compressed file and place it in a user-accessible location.

Why is this required in a real enterprise environment?

In enterprise systems, this type of task is very common for:

Developer data handover

Backup before access revocation

Migration to another server

Audit or compliance requests

User exit / role change

Instead of giving raw directory access, admins archive data to:

Preserve structure

Reduce size

Prevent accidental modification

Enable secure transfers

Which server(s) does this apply to and why?
âœ… Storage Server (Nautilus Storage Server)

Why?

The /data directory physically resides on the storage server

NAS / centralized storage is designed for shared developer data

This task must be executed where the data lives, not on app or DB servers

âŒ Not on:

App servers (stapp01/02/03)

Load balancer

DB server

2ï¸âƒ£ Prerequisites & Assumptions
Required User Access

sudo or root access is required

/data is typically owned by root or restricted groups

Archiving requires read access to all files

âœ” Recommended:

sudo -i

Required Files / Services

Directory must exist:

/data/mariyam


tar utility must be installed
(Default on all enterprise Linux distributions)

Important Checks Before Starting
1. Confirm directory exists
ls -ld /data/mariyam

2. Ensure sufficient disk space in /home
df -h /home

3. Confirm no active write operations (best practice)

Avoid archiving while files are being modified

Prevents partial or inconsistent backups

3ï¸âƒ£ Exact Commands (Step-by-Step)
Step 1: Switch to root (recommended)
sudo -i

Explanation

Ensures full read access

Prevents permission-related failures

Why this is best

Enterprise systems avoid repeated sudo calls

Reduces command interruption risk

Step 2: Create the compressed archive
tar -czvf mariyam.tar.gz /data/mariyam

Line-by-line explanation

tar â†’ Tape Archive utility (standard in Linux)

-c â†’ Create a new archive

-z â†’ Compress using gzip

-v â†’ Verbose (shows progress, useful for admins)

-f mariyam.tar.gz â†’ Output file name

/data/mariyam â†’ Source directory

Why this command is the best choice

Industry standard

Preserves:

Permissions

Ownership

Directory structure

Compatible across Linux systems

Step 3: Move the archive to /home
mv mariyam.tar.gz /home/

Explanation

Moves the archive to a user-accessible, non-system directory

Why /home?

Safer than /root

Common location for:

Downloads

Transfers

SFTP access

4ï¸âƒ£ Verification & Validation
1. Verify archive exists
ls -lh /home/mariyam.tar.gz

Expected output (example)
-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 120M Jan 19  mariyam.tar.gz

2. Verify archive contents (without extracting)
tar -tzf /home/mariyam.tar.gz

Expected behavior

Lists all files inside /data/mariyam

No error messages

3. Confirm archive integrity
gzip -t /home/mariyam.tar.gz

Expected output

No output â†’ archive is valid

